President Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama expressed their condolences to the family of Ernie Banks, as well as to the people of Chicago and baseball fans who loved him. They highlighted Banks' journey from the Negro Leagues to becoming the first African-American player for the Chicago Cubs and having his number retired. In addition to his achievements on the field, Banks was known for his positive attitude, love of the game, and being an ambassador for baseball. Michelle Obama shared her personal connection to Banks, as she used to watch him play on TV with her father when she was a girl. In 2013, President Obama honored Banks with the Presidential Medal of Freedom. The statement concludes with a reference to Banks' iconic nickname, "Mr. Cub," and his eternal readiness to play.